To encode a long string into a short string for sharing via a URL, you can use Base64 encoding. Base64 encoding converts binary data into ASCII characters, making it suitable for URL encoding. Here's a simple example of how you can achieve this in JavaScript:

```javascript
function encodeString(longString) {
  return btoa(longString);
}

function decodeString(shortString) {
  return atob(shortString);
}

// Example usage:
const longString = "This is a long string that needs to be encoded.";
const shortString = encodeString(longString);
console.log("Encoded string:", shortString);

const decodedString = decodeString(shortString);
console.log("Decoded string:", decodedString);
```

In this example, `btoa()` is used to encode the long string into a Base64 encoded string, and `atob()` is used to decode the Base64 encoded string back into the original long string.

Keep in mind that Base64 encoding will increase the length of the string, but it will still be shorter than the original string. The maximum length of the encoded string will be approximately 1.33 times the length of the original string.

